data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely** in EF Core 11. All four methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there's no configuration to re-enable them.

**Every sync LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` must become async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key things to do:**
1. Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` / sync opt-in from your `DbContextOptionsBuilder` — the API no longer exists and won't compile.
2. Convert all sync LINQ terminators (`ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`, etc.) to their `*Async` counterparts.
3. Convert `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`.
4. Propagate `async/await` up through callers (controllers, services, etc.).

`Add()` is fine — it's an in-memory tracking call, not I/O.
